1st rowOur adventure starts off inLa Cerdanya valley, in the Pyrenees, which is one of the largest valleys in Europe. Here we will cross part of Catalonia fromLa Cerdanya toBarcelona,travelling on secondary roads with beautiful landscapes. This route through Catalonia will be accompanied by the excellent Mediterranean climate, which is ideal for cycling as it allows riders to enjoy the best sensations while on their bike. An excellent opportunity to get to know this region, its people, customs and this environment of great natural and cultural value, which also offers great gastronomic options.
2nd rowIn La Cerdanya, one of the largest valleys in Europe, we have good temperatures, a dry climate,and a beautiful landready for you to discover it cycling. We offer you aweek ofactive holidaysand switching off from everyday life. Amidst an environment of great natural and cultural value, with great gastronomic options, where your only concern will be to cycle and enjoy the breathtaking scenery of thePyrenees. An excellent opportunity to get to know this region, its people, customs and this environment of great natural and cultural value, which also offers great gastronomic options.
3rd rowWe have planned this trip for those who love cycling and want to spend aweek pedalling, across part of Catalonia, from thePyrenees to the Costa Brava, along secondary roads and through amazingly beautiful landscapes. The first partof our tour focuses on the magnificent area of the Pyrenees and pre-Pyrenees and is of moderate difficulty. Here we will have the chance to discover some works belonging to the Catalan Romanesque period. The second partof the route runs along green tracks and is low difficulty, taking us straight to the Costa Brava. The route runs through La Garrotxa, the famous volcanic area in Catalonia, and stops in Girona city, with its wonderful old town, full of narrow streets that take us back to the middle ages. During the entire route, we will enjoy the local gastronomy and its people.
4th rowIn La Cerdanya, one of the largest valleys in Europe, we have good temperatures, a dry climate,and a beautiful landready for you to discover it trekking. We offer you aweek ofactive holidaysand switching off from everyday life. Amidst an environment of great natural and cultural value, with great gastronomic options, where your only concern will be tohike around the breathtaking scenery of thePyrenees. An excellent opportunity to get to know this region, its people, customs and this environment of great natural and cultural value, which also offers great gastronomic options.
5th rowIn La Cerdanya, one of the largest valleys in Europe, we have good temperatures, a dry climate,and a beautiful landready for you to discover it trekking. We offer you aweek ofactive holidaysand switching off from everyday life. Amidst an environment of great natural and cultural value, with great gastronomic options, where your only concern will be tohike around the breathtaking scenery of thePyrenees. An excellent opportunity to get to know this region, its people, customs and this environment of great natural and cultural value, which also offers great gastronomic options.

Food and DrinksFree Paris Walking Tour puts you into the hands of a trusted local expert because they come with years of experience and vast knowledge.\n\nThe Latin Quarter has been home to many generations of students for several centuries. Its name comes from the many schools and universities that are found in this district. Since the Middle Ages, the Latin Quarter has built its reputation primarily on the schools located there. The Sorbonne, Assas, the Ecole Normale Suprieure on rue dUlm, and the high schools Louis le Grand or Henri IV are all examples of the prestigious establishments found in the Latin Quarter.\nThis student tradition dates back to the 13th century, when many colleges were founded in the neighborhood. This was the case of the University of the Sorbonne, the college created by Robert de Sorbon in 1257. The name of the district also comes from the medieval times.
